<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-133-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 133 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Mini-Micro Systems  March 1989 v22 n3 p66(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gotcha! (optical scanners)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wood, Lamont.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scanners come in a variety of forms, resolutions and price ranges.andO;A typical scanner will have 300 dpi resolution, but some modelscan produce 2,000 dpi images.andP;  Price ranges can start as low as$300 and reach several thousand dollars.andP;  Scanner resolutiondepends on the density of the charge-coupled device element thatis contained within every model.andP;  A key specification to determinewithin a scanner is the variation between 'base' and 'scaled'resolution.andP;  Base resolution measures the total capacity of thescanner.andP;  Scaled resolution measures the amount of magnificationor reduction that is possible.andP;  A variety of interfaces is alsoavailable, which determines the amount of scan time needed.andO;Scanning can also be slowed down by complex software andrestricted available memory.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ScanningAdd-In-On DevicesDesktop PublishingSpecificationsImaging TechnologyI-O Devices.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Text-image scanners. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>